 incentives to promote social mobility.</gtr:title><gtr:parentPublicationTitle>BMJ (Clinical research ed.)</gtr:parentPublicationTitle><gtr:authors><gtr:author url="http://gtr.ukri.org:80/person/762e3bbd5f087d25c4960c0097cfef74"><gtr:id>762e3bbd5f087d25c4960c0097cfef74</gtr:id><gtr:otherNames>Forde I</gtr:otherNames></gtr:author></gtr:authors><gtr:date>2009-01-01</gtr:date><gtr:issn>0959-535X</gtr:issn><gtr:outcomeId>9E9B1DD32A0</gtr:outcomeId></gtr:publication><gtr:publication><gtr:id>632C4FEC-2FBB-4473-9FAF-2A8ED6F84398</gtr:id><gtr:title>Using conditionality as a solution to the problem of low uptake of essential services among disadvantaged communities: a social determinants view.</gtr:title><gtr:parentPublicationTitle>American journal of public health</gtr:parentPublicationTitle><gtr:authors><gtr:author url="http://gtr.ukri.org:80/person/762e3bbd5f087d25c4960c0097cfef74"><gtr:id>762e3bbd5f087d25c4960c0097cfef74</gtr:id><gtr:otherNames>Forde I</gtr:otherNames></gtr:author></gtr:authors><gtr:date>2011-01-01</gtr:date><gtr:issn>0090-0036</gtr:issn><gtr:outcomeId>NJA1ghoaAKo</gtr:outcomeId></gtr:publication></gtr:publications><gtr:identifiers><gtr:identifier type="RCUK">G0701333</gtr:identifier></gtr:identifiers><gtr:healthCategories><gtr:healthCategory><gtr:id>F3822669-BB5A-4BB4-BAE0-DCB9DE36E092</gtr:id><gtr:percentage>100</gtr:percentage><gtr:text>Generic Health Relevance</gtr:text></gtr:healthCategory></gtr:healthCategories><gtr:researchActivities><gtr:researchActivity><gtr:id>5841ECCD-C9B1-4B8B-993F-ACC8E9585125</gtr:id><gtr:percentage>100</gtr:percentage><gtr:text>3.1  Primary preventions interventions to modify behaviours or promote well-being</gtr:text></gtr:researchActivity></gtr:researchActivities><gtr:researchSubjects/><gtr:researchTopics/><gtr:rcukProgrammes/></gtr:project></gtr:projectComposition></gtr:projectOverview>